string



- is immutable (like in Java)
- triple quotes allow for multiline strings
- slicing possible (1)
- methods
    - split(sep, maxsplit) (1)
        - 1st arg: delimiter string or regex
            - if not given, defaults to whitespace
        - 2nd arg: how many splits at most (from left to right)
            - by default, no limit
        - returns new list
    - join(iterable) (2)
        - single arg: iterable of strings
        - string on which method is called is inserted in between each elem
        - returns new string
    - replace(old, new, count) (3)
        - 1st arg: to be replaced
        - 2nd arg: replacement
        - 3rd arg: how many occurences to be replaced (optional)
            - defaults to -1, i.e. replace all occurences
    - upper()/lower() returns string str in upper/lower case

EXAMPLE
(1)
name = "joedoe"
res = name[0:3] + 'y ' + name[3:]
print(res)  # joey doe

(2)
res = name.split("oe")
print(res)  # jd

(3)
res = " ".join(["cats", "dogs", "mice"])
print(res)  # cats dogs mice

(4)
res = "beer".replace("e", "i", 1)
print(res)  # bier
